              "role": "assistant",
              "content": [
                {
                  "kind": "text",
                  "data": "There's no single \"default password\" stored in PostgreSQL config files — PostgreSQL doesn't store passwords in plaintext in its configuration.\n\nHere's how to find/reset it:\n\n**1. Check your Laravel `.env` file (quickest)**\n\nYour app already has the credentials:\n\n```bash\ngrep DB_ .env\n```\n\nLook for `DB_PASSWORD`.\n\n**2. If using Docker (your setup)**\n\nThe password is set via environment variables in your Docker Compose file. Check:\n\n```bash\ngrep -r POSTGRES_PASSWORD docker/\n```\n\n**3. If you need to reset it (local PostgreSQL)**\n\nOn macOS, the default `postgres` user often has no password with peer/trust auth. You can reset it:\n\n```bash\n# Connect without password (trust auth)\npsql -U postgres\n\n# Then set a password\nALTER USER postgres PASSWORD 'newpassword';\n```\n\n**4. Check pg_hba.conf auth method**\n\n```bash\n# Find the file\npsql -U postgres -c \"SHOW hba_file;\"\n# Or common locations:\n# macOS Homebrew: /opt/homebrew/var/postgresql@15/pg_hba.conf\n# Linux: /etc/postgresql/*/main/pg_hba.conf\n```\n\nIf `pg_hba.conf` shows `trust` for local connections, no password is needed. If it shows `md5` or `scram-sha-256`, a password is required but it's stored as a hash (not recoverable — only resettable).\n\n**TL;DR:** Check your `.env` or `docker/` compose files — that's where your project's DB password lives."
                }
              ],
